x4codes.hlp: Los Alamos National Laboratory, NM, United States of America

x4freetext: Los Alamos Neutron Scattering Center,
59.4-m flight path
Neutrons created by 800 MeV proton pulse onto
a tungsten target and moderated to low energies using
chilled water.
Solid metal sample in the form of a rectangle
7.7 cm x 6.3 cm and 1.3 cm thick, enriched to 87.6%
in 117Sn and placed in the center of the detector.
Radiative capture measurement.
Array of 24 CsI crystals with approximately
3.5 pi of detection solid angle. Crystals packed
tightly around the target in two arrays of
12 crystals each, with a 10-cm cylindrical hole
through the middle to allow access for the neutron
beam.
3HE scintillation detector of very well known
efficiency to determine the power law exponent in the
neutron flux.
Flight path length determined by fitting peaks to known
neutron resonance energies in 232Th and other samples.
Neutron flux and detector efficiency obtained by
fitting the detector count to known resonance
parameters in 117Sn.
Corrected using FITXS code for all major corrections
of the neutron TOF spectra - moderation time, detector
efficiencies, flight path length, target temperature,
proton pulse width.
Also corrected for
. dead time (<35%),
. neutron capture after multiple scattering
(about 25%),
. contribution of trace amounts of Mn (in the vacuum
windows) made to the 342-eV and 358-eV resonances
(40% and 5% respectively).
No reply from J.D.Bowman to author proof.
IS
Resonance parameters obtained using the time-of-flight
spectra and the fitting code FITXS. Orbital angular
momentum assignments made with a Bayesian analysis.
